</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Widespread in Europe and west Asia (
<bibRefCitation author="Gagne, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" refId="B12" refString="Gagne, RJ, Jaschhof, M, 2017. A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp. https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" title="A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp." url="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" year="2017">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gagné">Gagne</normalizedToken>
and Jaschhof 2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="gall and life history">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Gall and life history.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kieffer" baseAuthorityYear="1890" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Massalongiaceae" genus="Massalongia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Massalongia rubra" order="Peltigerales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Massalongia rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
induces barely noticeable midrib leaf galls on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula pubescens" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Betula pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ehrh. and other 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. (
<bibRefCitation author="Gagne, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" refId="B12" refString="Gagne, RJ, Jaschhof, M, 2017. A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp. https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" title="A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp." url="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" year="2017">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gagné">Gagne</normalizedToken>
and Jaschhof 2017
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kieffer, JJ" editor="Wytsman, P" journalOrPublisher="V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 346" refId="B24" refString="Kieffer, JJ, 1913b. Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc. In: Wytsman, P, Ed., Genera Insectorum. V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles: 1 - 346" title="Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc." volumeTitle="Genera Insectorum." year="1913 b">Kieffer 1913b</bibRefCitation>
). The females lay eggs on young leaves in May, and most mature larvae leave the galls to overwinter in the ground in October, but some hibernate in the galls (
<bibRefCitation author="Skuhrava, M" journalOrPublisher="Ziemsen Verlag, Wittenberg Lutherstadt" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B36" refString="Skuhrava, M, Skuhravy, V, 1973. Gallmuecken und ihre Gallen auf Wildpflanzen. Die Neue Brehmbuecherei. A. Ziemsen Verlag, Wittenberg Lutherstadt" title="Gallmuecken und ihre Gallen auf Wildpflanzen. Die Neue Brehmbuecherei. A." year="1973">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Skuhravá">Skuhrava</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Skuhravý">Skuhravy</normalizedToken>
1973
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The larval specimens we described here were collected from similar galls to those described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kieffer, JJ" editor="Wytsman, P" journalOrPublisher="V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 346" refId="B24" refString="Kieffer, JJ, 1913b. Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc. In: Wytsman, P, Ed., Genera Insectorum. V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles: 1 - 346" title="Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc." volumeTitle="Genera Insectorum." year="1913 b">Kieffer (1913b)</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. rubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the larval morphology fits 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kieffer’s">Kieffer's</normalizedToken>
description and illustrations, thus we believe they indeed belong to 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. rubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Types of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. rubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, like most of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kieffer’s">Kieffer's</normalizedToken>
types, are considered lost (
<bibRefCitation author="Gagne, RJ" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" refId="B12" refString="Gagne, RJ, Jaschhof, M, 2017. A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp. https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" title="A Catalog of the Cecidomyiidae (Diptera) of the World. Fourth Edition. Digital version, 762 pp." url="https://www.ars.usda.gov/ARSUserFiles/80420580/Gagne_2017_World_Cat_4th_ed.pdf" year="2017">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gagné">Gagne</normalizedToken>
and Jaschhof 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). We considered using one larva for designating a neotype for the species, but because no adults were reared from these larvae, we cannot be completely certain about their identity and decided to refrain from doing so. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kieffer, JJ" editor="Wytsman, P" journalOrPublisher="V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 346" refId="B24" refString="Kieffer, JJ, 1913b. Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc. In: Wytsman, P, Ed., Genera Insectorum. V. Verteneuil &amp; L. Desmet, Bruxelles: 1 - 346" title="Diptera. Fam. Cecidomyiidae. Fasc." volumeTitle="Genera Insectorum." year="1913 b">Kieffer (1913b)</bibRefCitation>
provided an illustration of male terminalia showing that the species is distinctive from the other known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1897" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Massalongiaceae" genus="Massalongia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Massalongia" order="Peltigerales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Massalongia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its long and apically enlarged aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 52–54" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figures 52 - 54. Massalongia rubra. 52 male terminalia (after Kieffer 1913 b) 53 spatula 54 dorsal view of larval terminal abdominal segments (a the inner four terminal papillae are folded on the segment b the inner four terminal papillae are unfolded in another specimen). Scale bars: 50 µm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.958.54300.figures52-54" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/440978" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">52</figureCitation>
). Because this illustration is important for separating species and it was drawn from the type specimen, future designation of a neotype for the species must rely on reared adults that will enable to compare characters of the male terminalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
